In a letter to Apple chief executive, Tim Cook, the Minnesota Democrat asked for more clarity on security questions.

‘If someone hacks your password, you can change it – as many times as you want,’ said Senator Franken, in his letter.

‘You can’t change your fingerprints. You have only ten of them. And you leave them on everything you touch; they are definitely not a secret.’

Apple claims this kind of technology boosts security for users.

It added that the fingerprint data is stored on the phone in a place that's inaccessible to other apps and to Apple's remote servers.

