Senator Franken said that, unlike a string of numbers, a fingerprint uniquely identifies its owner.

‘Let me put it this way,’ he said. ‘If hackers get a hold of your thumbprint, they could use it to identify and impersonate you for the rest of your life.’

Apple is yet to issue an official response to Senator Franken, but it has published a support document on its website outlining the security features of Touch ID.

‘Touch ID does not store any images of your fingerprint. It stores only a mathematical representation of your fingerprint,’ it said.

‘It isn’t possible for your actual fingerprint image to be reverse-engineered from this mathematical representation.’

‘Your fingerprint data is never accessed by iOS or other apps, never stored on Apple servers, and never backed up to iCloud or anywhere else,’ it added.

